headline: Rate-Cut Hopes Bolster These Stocks. Two Top Buy Points.
summary: Consumer stocks led the stock market Tuesday, as investors pounced on retail, travel and other splurge-on-me stocks.  Economic data was largely disappointing but appeared to raise hopes of another interest-rate cut.  In afternoon trading, eight of the 12 best-performing industry groups were from the retail sector — each up more than 4% and leading IBD's ranking of 197 groups.

headline: Walmart Is Exploring Bringing Ads to Sparky, Its New AI Shopping Agent
summary: Walmart  is testing ads in its new AI shopping agent, Sparky.  The world’s largest retailer has quietly been exploring new ad formats with some advertisers, according to people familiar with the matter.  One ad type dubbed “Sponsored Prompt,” is a new type of ad that has been tested in Sparky, which the company added to its mobile app in June, the people said.

headline: Why Walmart's AI Robotics Maker Is Soaring Over 30%
summary: Symbotic, a maker of AI-enabled robotic technologies for automating warehouses and distribution centers that has Walmart as a major customer, late Monday beat estimates for its fiscal fourth quarter, with adjusted profit soaring.  On a nonadjusted basis, Symbotic reported a quarterly loss of 3 cents per share, slightly above expectations of a 4-cent loss.  For the full fiscal year, Symbotic saw earnings per share of $2.02, soaring vs. EPS of 12 cents in fiscal 2024.

headline: Why This Robotics Stock Has Soared 40% After Earnings
summary: Symbotic stock was up 39% to $75.88 in late morning trading Tuesday.  Much of the gain came because the company said the medical-supply distributor Medline is a new customer, its first in the healthcare sector.  “Announcing Medline as a customer opens a new end-market and validates SYM’s ability to support lofty growth expectations,” wrote Oppenheimer & Co analysts in a research note Tuesday.

headline: Retail Sales Finally Land. There Are These Red Flags for the U.S. Economy.
summary: The first glimpse of official consumer spending data in two months is in: retail sales rose at a slower pace than expected in September.  Economists polled by FactSet were expecting a 0.4% jump.  Stripping out sales of vehicles, car parts, and gasoline, retail sales rose just 0.1%, below forecasts for a 0.4% increase.
